description:
The Funday Times was a section of the UK Sunday Times. It was intended mainly for children, and included several comics, including Dennis and Gnasher, Rex and Tex, Beryl the Peril, Fans Utd., Scooby Doo, Space Raoul, The Powerpuff Girls, Creature Feature, Newton's Law, Jarvis, Squirt, The Flintstones, Robot Crusoe, Goosebumps and The Simpsons. Launched in 1989 it originally featured adult cartoons like Modesty Blaise but quickly dropped them in favour of more child friendly fare such as Asterix.

It also included reviews of various toys and songs, interviews with celebrities, including Will Smith, Gail Emms and Matt Groening, and interesting events coming up during the week.

The last printed edition of the Funday Times was published on Sunday 12 March 2006. After that date, it was only available online. The print edition of the Funday Times ran for nearly 20 years before it was discontinued. The website mostly concentrated on features and games, although there were comic strips on the website that were originally in the printed version.

The Funday Times website closed down on 5 January 2007.
name: Funday Times

deck: Second attempt at the digital edition, after the first volume was plagued with technical problems and bugs.
description:
After The Dandy ended it's print run in December 2012, they launched a new digital version. Unfortunately, there was numerous bugs and technical issues. Having ironed out these problems, it was decided to restart, with the old issues being taken down and their content re-released in a new volume, with readers receiving the equivalent new issue for each issue they'd paid for.

One additional change is that the Desperate Dan strips now have voice acting as well as the traditional speech bubbles.

Alas, after 13 issues, this run also ended, with the title retired for good. The Dandy Annual will continue, but The Beano is now the last of the DC Thomson humour anthologies.
name: The Dandy
